<br>
I knew you were kidding.  That's why I said welcome to America.  And I was serious.  Welcome to your new home.<br>
<br>
For all our faults, it's home.  Either I missed it, or it wasn't mentioned, but where do you call home now?  If in a snowy clime, go out and enjoy the snow for a bit.  Fall on your back, and wave your arms and legs to make snow angels.  Build a snowman.  Have a snowball fight with your loved one.  Then hate the snow when the snow plows shovel more of it back into your driveway, and gripe because it isn't the white stuff, but hard slushy brown stuff that hardens like cement behind your car.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Why do you think I live in Arizona now?  lol.<br>
<br>
Below is a joke that I have that I will change to an Australian instead of a Californian.  Enjoy.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Australian man moves to America in winter<br>
Jan 10<br>
It's starting to snow.  The first of the season and the first I've ever seen.  The girlfriend and I took our hot buttered rums and sat by the picture window, watching the snowflakes drift down, clinging to the trees and covering the ground.  It was breathtaking.<br>
<br>
Jan 11<br>
Well, we awoke to a lovely blanket of crystal white snow covering the landscape.  What a fantastic sight.  Every tree and shrub was covered with a beautiful mantle.  I shovelled snow for the first time, and loved it.  I did the driveway and our sidewalk.  Later, a city snowplow came along and accidentally covered up the driveway with compacted snow from the street.  The driver smiled and waved.  I waved back and shovelled it again.<br>
<br>
Jan 12<br>
It snowed an additional five inches last night, and the temperature dropped to around eleven degrees.  Several tree limbs broke off from the weight of the snow.  I shovelled the driveway again.  Shortly afterwards, the snowplow came and did his little trick again.  This time, the snow was a grayish brown.<br>
<br>
Jan 13<br>
Warmed up enough during the day to melt the snow, turning it into slush, which became ice when the temperature dropped again.  Bought snow tires for both cars.  Fell on my arse in the driveway and went to the emergency room.  Nothing broken, thankfully.  More ice and snow expected later.<br>
<br>
Jan 14<br>
Still cold today.  Sold a car and bought a 4x4 in order to get to work.  Slid into a guardrail and did considerable damage to the right front quarter panel.  Another eight inches of the white crap fell again last night.  Both vehicles are covered with salt and crud.  More shovelling in store for me.  The snowplow came by twice today.  Damn him.<br>
<br>
Jan 15<br>
Two degrees at noon today.  More freaking snow.  Not a tree or shrub is left in our yard that hasn't been damaged.  Power was off all night.  Tried to keep from freezing to death with candles and a kerosene heater, which tipped over, nearly burning the house down.  Got 2nd degree burns on both hands, and lost my eyelashes and eyebrows.  Car slid on the ice on the way to the hospital and was totalled.<br>
<br>
Jan 16<br>
Damn mother freaking more white crap keeps coming down!  Had to put on every item of clothes I own just to go to the mailbox just to find he didn't even come today.  If I ever catch the S.O.B. of a snowplow driver, I will rip open his chest, and rip out his heart.  Power still off, toilet is frozen and cracking, and part of the roof is caving in now.<br>
<br>
Jan 17<br>
Six more inches of that damn, freaking white crap fell again, and freaking ice, and freaking sleet and God only knows what other kind of crap.  I wounded the snowplow driver with an ice pick, but he managed to escape.  Girlfirend is frozen like a popsicle.  Car wont start.  I think I am going snowblind.  I can't move my toes.  Haven't seen the sun in weeks.  More snow is predicted.  Windchill is 30 degrees below zero.  Moving back to Australia.<br>
<br>
Or in your case, Zora, move to Arizona.  Then you will have to contend with 115+ heat in summer.  hehehehe..&quot;But it's a dry heat....&quot;<br>
